  "reasoning_summary": "The participation elasticity for single mothers has been studied extensively in the context of EITC expansions and welfare reform. Eissa and Liebman (1996) found substantial labor force participation responses among single mothers to the 1986 EITC expansion, implying elasticities around 0.7-1.0. Subsequent work by Saez, Chetty, and others has generally supported the finding that single mothers are relatively responsive to tax incentives at the extensive margin, with central estimates typically in the 0.5-1.0 range. The elasticity may be somewhat lower in more recent periods due to changing labor market conditions and policy environments, hence the left tail. The upper tail reflects estimates from some studies that find very large responses during welfare reform periods when EITC and other transfer changes coincided."
}

