  "reasoning_summary": "The EITC expansions of the 1990s and associated research provide a strong empirical basis. Eissa and Liebman (1996) found substantial participation responses among single mothers to the 1986 EITC expansion, with implied elasticities around 0.5-1.0. Meyer and Rosenbaum (2001) found even larger effects when considering welfare reform and tax changes together, with participation elasticities in the range of 0.7-1.3. The literature generally finds that single mothers are among the most elastic groups in terms of labor force participation with respect to net-of-tax wages, reflecting both the salience of the EITC and the relatively low baseline participation rates. My midpoint of ~0.65 reflects the moderate end of these estimates, weighting toward studies that isolate tax variation from confounding policy changes, while allowing for a wide range given heterogeneity across reforms and identification strategies."
}

