  "reasoning_summary": "The literature on single mothers' labor supply, particularly surrounding the EITC expansions in the 1980s and 1990s, consistently finds relatively high participation elasticities compared to other demographic groups. Eissa and Liebman (1996) estimated participation elasticities around 0.7-1.0 for single mothers in response to TRA86. Meyer and Rosenbaum (2001) found similar magnitudes when studying welfare reform and tax changes. Structural estimates from Keane and Moffitt (1998) and related work also support elasticities in this range. The extensive margin (participation) tends to be more responsive than the intensive margin (hours), and single mothers face particularly high implicit marginal tax rates from benefit phase-outs, making the net-of-tax wage elasticity a policy-relevant parameter. I center my estimate around 0.8 with uncertainty reflecting variation across studies, time periods, and estimation methods."
}

