  "citations": ["Keane (2011) JEL survey", "Chetty (2012) bounds on Frisch elasticity", "Prescott (2004) macro calibration arguments"],
  "reasoning_summary": "The Frisch elasticity at the intensive margin for prime-age workers is generally estimated to be modest. Microeconometric studies using male prime-age workers often find values near 0.1-0.3, while macro/lifecycle calibrations (e.g., Prescott, Rogerson) typically use values around 0.5-1.0 to match aggregate labor supply variation. Chetty (2012) argues bounds place it around 0.5-0.8 when reconciling micro and macro evidence. Keane's (2011) survey suggests the true value likely lies between the low micro estimates and the higher macro-calibrated values. I center my median at 0.5, reflecting the consensus reconciling estimate, with a wide upper tail acknowledging that some macro calibrations successfully use values near 1.0 or slightly above."
}

